      <hedline>
        <hl1>Double Green</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Darren Goetze of Union of Concerned Scientists praises Bill McKibben's May 3 Op-Ed article as wake-up call on emissions of heat-trapping gases and global warming (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bill McKibben's wake-up call on global warming (Op-Ed, May 3) could not have come at a better time. In less than seven months, the world's governments will gather in Japan to decide how to reduce emissions of heat-trapping gases that are changing our climate and threatening human health and the environment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bill McKibben's wake-up call on global warming (Op-Ed, May 3) could not have come at a better time. In less than seven months, the world's governments will gather in Japan to decide how to reduce emissions of heat-trapping gases that are changing our climate and threatening human health and the environment.</p>
        <p>Many forward-thinking businesses -- like the reinsurance industry and high-technology companies -- are joining scientists in the call for action, because the technology for cost-effective solutions exists today. For example, Vermont's Green Mountain Power Corporation has reduced electricity consumption through energy-efficiency programs, saving its customers $5 million a year.</p>
        <p>With a cooperative plan involving government, industry and individuals, we can simultaneously protect our fragile climate and bolster the bottom line.</p>
        <p>DARREN GOETZE  Cambridge, Mass., May 5, 1997</p>
        <p>The writer is a staff scientist at the Union of Concerned Scientists.</p>
        <p>Greenhouse Theory Inflates Human Significance</p>
      </block>
